Use `switchMap` instead 

&quot;The main difference between switchMap and other flattening operators is the cancelling effect. On each emission the previous inner observable (the result of the function you supplied) is cancelled and the new observable is subscribed. &quot; [read more on switchMap](https://www.learnrxjs.io/operators/transformation/switchmap.html)

[stackblitz example](https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-3nxbtn)

```
import { Component } from &#39;@angular/core&#39;;
import { interval,of } from &#39;rxjs&#39;;
import { flatMap,switchMap } from &#39;rxjs/operators&#39;;
@Component({
  selector: &#39;my-app&#39;,
  templateUrl: &#39;./app.component.html&#39;,
  styleUrls: [ &#39;./app.component.css&#39; ]
})
export class AppComponent  {
  name = &#39;Angular&#39;;
  currentTime$ = of(1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8)
  ngOnInit() {
    const int = interval(5000);

    const subscription = int
      .pipe(switchMap(() =&gt; this.currentTime$ ))
      .subscribe(val =&gt; console.log(&quot;TIME&quot;, val));
      }
}
```

